	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Denekamp</placeName> the</p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>1862</date></p>
				<p rend="align(center)">My beloved uncle&#33;</p>
				<p>Now I find me obliged my dear to answer you<lb/> on your writing&#59; and hope that you may read these<lb/> rules in the best situation.  As for me I am as well<lb/> as heart can wish&#59; although one is not always in the<lb/> best order that is naturally&#59; then the man is submitted<lb/> to all&#59; and one is often troubled with many distempers&#44;<lb/> but that is all ordered so <sic>trough</sic> the omnipotence<lb/> of our heavenly Father&#59; and if one is troubled sometimes<lb/> through some adversity one must think all what<lb/> God does is <sic>weldone</sic>.  Now my dear uncle I must<lb/> make you mention&#44; that when we have received your<lb/> portrait it <sic>maked</sic> us a great joy what you well can<lb/> think&#59; and I thank you with all my heart that you<lb/> have had the goodness as to send it us.  Now can I<lb/> see you&#44; and if I regard it I wished you were by us<lb/> then could I look you yet better&#59; but I am also content<lb/> with your picture when it can not others.  Now I can<lb/> write you yet my news.  In the month of <date>May</date> a dread&#44;<lb/>ful fire <sic>hitted</sic> the city of <placeName><hi rend="underline">Enschede</hi></placeName> &#40;what is situated<lb/> four hour from us&#41;&#44; the whole city is destoryed&#59; no single<lb/> house is delivered.  My father&#44; my sister and I have<lb/> been there to see also these desolation&#44; but what<lb/> a terrible sight&#33; all men are out of the city and here<lb/> and there divulged.  The number of houses what is</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>about twelve hundred&#44; three church and one church<lb/> of the Israelites&#59; all the sephers are retrieved.  My dear<lb/> uncle you have nothing written from my picture how<lb/> it liked you&#59; write it me now if you please.  Your<lb/> books what you send me come well over every month<lb/> and I read in it yet often with great pleasure.<lb/>  At this moment I <sic>now</sic> nothing more to write you&#44;<lb/> another time more thus I must now finish with this<lb/> and I hope that it may be sufficient to you.  Farewell<lb/> my dear uncle&#44; and wish to receive speedy from you a great<lb/> letter.  Many times saluted from me and with this<lb/> I make the end&#59; and I am with all reverence</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your affectionate niece</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">Jeanette Elkus</persName></p>
				<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
